[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Git environment setup**\n\nI’m considering if the environment or system properties can customize the git command. The TCK environment notably includes git, and Ubuntu-latest has it too. Tests can build commands without execution, but it seems there's an issue with compile-only setups. We might need resolved artifacts and dependencies since no external server is necessary. I’m wondering if we should choose between \"no action\" or \"advisory preparation\" depending on what research reveals about additional setup needs for the Git CLI.\n\n**Considering test-code setup**\n\nI’m thinking that the \"other test-code setup\" might involve using a temporary local git repository and local configuration. Meaningful coverage for the git executable could only happen if the test scaffold runs the git executable. Normally, the generated scaffold for Java tests doesn't include a git repository, but it can create a temporary directory in the code. They mention \"beyond normal generated test scaffold,\" which could relate to maven dependencies, Docker, or environment settings. For a CLI git provider, I need the git executable installed, though there are no deterministic setups beyond maybe a Docker image.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_031364292d942632016a2a592fc1008194b1aeea097854a56b\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKllCJxeMgMeLpdFGE4poKzPJU4z8ktOJhF0rmHTVYZcxaL_qQDaWqBW00Xcpe-CwZwu6Fc119Hlro1ets1yFzRMVE6Y938LU6-EHDVdQ_44vcYVZ_prjHEPu9UEhaYBg-s80qXO3JYT7E0Y0s6G56k3v14bwv3be6Af_GrqfX8ynbIqK1U8HejmSQpxGh9TU5ZeAR72x41ZQ9faaEQ6_UrlpdWUlhl-efD9TttzXgLgo2ybNboMb5YMaCORZKfBpAKP_OOzMhjxe-xpM29xFU7lC9qsjt104prBGEPHgK4bHw_TW7TIkpOKoGEJDc-zUrX7gJqpIogNXDjLeeD_KMYGbyzgkNyyh3oVw8WG57QAMRv7Q7mLmZxtvwRxYf8ZcylucjJ-o6z6pj9-IVXCB0_jrHslDbazt1hGEb_kxQ1hCNRLqitn_CbTEDwwGA31aVgxZnEod7mZ9Pk8XcvrA-aiFNeD26H98L4dpPQ1Q--6zVygqCq5BWia-3xv9O